Vol. I 64 ff. and the authorities there cited. Q. Pedius, a nephew of C. Julius Caesar, was praetor 483 was sent in 45 as legatus against the Pompeian forces in Spain, receiving the honors of a triumph in the same year. On his election to the consulship, he passed the so-called lex Pedia, by which the assassins of Caesar were punished with ‘aquae et ignis interdictio! He was in charge of Rome when the news of the formation of the second triumvirate and the proscriptions reached him. He with great difficulty prevented an open insur- rection‚ but overcome with fatigue expired suddenly on the fol- lowing night.
